        <descriptionSet>
            <description pref="false" source="Arthur M. Sackler Gallery" dataDate="2015-11-30-19-03-00">
                <text>Carved of dark gray limestone, this imposing Buddha head is characterized by a serene yet remote expression that is typical of early Tang dynasty religious images. Imperial patronage of Buddhism during the Tang dynasty, approximately seven hundred years after knowledge of Buddhism first reached China, resulted in the creation of some of the most impressive sculptures in Chinese history. For this Buddha head, all traces of Indian and Central Asian influence have been replaced by a native Chinese aesthetic. Sculptures of this style are found in the Longmen cave temples in Henan Province and may have been the source for this piece.</text>
                <author>
                    <name refid="139247290" type="corporate" vocab="viaf">Arthur M. Sackler Gallery (Smithsonian Institution)</name>
                    <role type="code" vocab="marcrelator">aut</role>
                </author>
            </description>
            <description pref="true" source="Sackler Gallery online. www.asia.si.edu  Page: accessed 22 December 2006." dataDate="2016-06-08-15-51-25">
                <text>Probably from Longmen caves. Carved of dark gray limestone, this imposing Buddha head is characterized by a serene yet remote expression that is typical of early Tang dynasty religious images. Imperial patronage of Buddhism during the Tang dynasty, approximately seven hundred years after knowledge of Buddhism first reached China, resulted in the creation of some of the most impressive sculptures in Chinese history. For this Buddha head, all traces of Indian and Central Asian influence have been replaced by a native Chinese aesthetic. Sculptures of this style are found in the Longmen cave temples in Henan Province.</text>
